#. type: Plain text
#: origin/anti-spam-stuff.txt:266
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        1. There is a whitelist /var/dcc/whiteclnt. Whitelist everyone\n"
"you can think of - linuxfromscratch.org, ebay, paypal, and any other\n"
"list server you may be on. This bit '-S mail_host' told dccifd to\n"
"mention check mail_host in the header. This allows you to add mail_hosts\n"
"to /var/dcc/whiteclnt in the appropiate section. Putting in IPs is no\n"
"use. You can specify any header, but it only passes one, so don't\n"
"spacify mail_host if you want to use some other header.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/anti-spam-stuff.txt:271
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        2. There is a blacklist file, which isn't a lot of use as the\n"
"spammers have to keep hopping from one place to another anyhow.  If\n"
"certain weirdos stay stuck in the same place, they belong in a\n"
"blacklist.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/anti-spam-stuff.txt:284
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        3. Greylisting is also an option. You may theoretically lose a\n"
"small percentage of mail with this. It works as follows. In every mail\n"
"transaction where this is done, your mail server says \"Not right now -\n"
"I'm busy. Send it in half an hour\" Proper mail servers will send it\n"
"later. Poorly set up mail servers may lose mail, either by not sending,\n"
"or resending immediately and then giving up. Spammers will not resend in\n"
"99% of cases, seeing as they can't hold messages back while relaying\n"
"illegally through other servers with ease. So you don't get spammed, and\n"
"your name comes off their list. That's the theory. \n"
"\tForget this if you have pop or imap. You'll reject nothing -\n"
"just leave them on your server. This is for directly connected boxes\n"
"receiving their mail by smtp only.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/anti-spam-stuff.txt:293
msgid ""
"Some words on querying: dccproc is like razors check, except it reports as "
"well by default. If you check & report ham repeatedly with dcc, the count "
"keeps going up. Use the -Q option for repeat tests to avoid reporting "
"again.  Each user is supposed only to report each mail once.  For your "
"tests, cat message | dccproc -QC checks and computes checksums without "
"reporting.  I would suggest a startup script for dcc and spamd (The server "
"end of spamassassin). Mine is available."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/anti-spam-stuff.txt:298
msgid ""
"The threshold figure is set by -t. The three checksums are body, fuz1 and "
"fuz2. All are covered by the 'cmn' setting. DCC say to set them at 'many'. I "
"found results dissappointing, and set it to 20, where things worked "
"better. My dccifd options are"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/anti-spam-stuff.txt:306
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"-I luser:group  # Who it runs as. A real person, please.\n"
"\t\t# You need this or it runs as root!\n"
"-p /tmp/dccifd  # Location of socket. \n"
"-m /var/dcc/map # Location of map [Default /var/dcc/map}\n"
"-d -B set:debug # Debug (both options)\n"
"-x              # Try extra hard to connect to a server (I needed that)\n"
"-t cmn,20       # Set all thresholds to 20\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/anti-spam-stuff.txt:310
msgid ""
"Make sure to finish the 'stop' section with rm -f /tmp/dccifd to remove a "
"stray socket if it exists. An old socket or pid will prevent dccifd from "
"restarting."
